  "text": "The Prometheus Alertmanager notification pipeline in Grafana Mimir is orchestrated through the following key components:\n\n**1. Alert Ingestion:**\nAlerts are ingested through the in-memory alert storage implemented in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/provider/mem/mem.go`. The `Alerts` struct provides methods to store and retrieve alerts. In Grafana Mimir, the Alertmanager service (in `pkg/alertmanager/alertmanager.go`) creates an instance of `mem.Alerts` using `NewAlerts()` at line 297, which serves as the central alert store for a tenant.\n\n**2. Configuration and Pipeline Setup:**\nThe `ApplyConfig()` method in `pkg/alertmanager/alertmanager.go` (line 494) is the entry point for applying a new configuration. It orchestrates the setup of the entire notification pipeline by:\n- Creating inhibition rules via `inhibit.NewInhibitor()` at line 513\n- Building the routing tree as a `dispatch.Route` at line 537\n- Building the notification pipeline through `notify.PipelineBuilder.New()` at line 557\n- Creating the dispatcher via `dispatch.NewDispatcher()` at line 567\n\n**3. Routing Tree Traversal:**\nThe `Dispatcher` struct (in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/dispatch/dispatch.go`, line 83) is responsible for routing alerts through the alert routing tree. The `Run()` method (line 147) starts the main dispatcher loop by subscribing to alert updates via `d.alerts.Subscribe()` at line 157. The `Route` struct (defined in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/dispatch/route.go`, line 42) represents nodes in the routing tree with matchers and receiver configuration. The dispatcher matches incoming alerts against route matchers and groups them into aggregation groups.\n\n**4. Inhibition Check:**\nThe `Inhibitor` (in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/inhibit/inhibit.go`, line 36) determines whether an alert should be muted based on inhibition rules and currently active alerts. Created via `inhibit.NewInhibitor()` (line 47), it implements the Muter interface and checks alert label sets against inhibition rules to suppress notifications.\n\n**5. Silence Check:**\nThe `Silences` struct (in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/silence/silence.go`, line with Silence package) manages the silence database which stores configured silences that suppress alert notifications. In `pkg/alertmanager/alertmanager.go`, a `silence.Silences` instance is created at line 257 and integrated into the pipeline at line 561 via `silence.NewSilencer()`.\n\n**6. Final Notifier Dispatch:**\nThe `PipelineBuilder` (in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/notify/notify.go`, line 382) constructs the notification pipeline with all processing stages. The `New()` method (line 395) builds the pipeline stages that process alerts through:\n- Inhibition checking via the inhibitor\n- Silence checking\n- Time interval evaluation\n- Notification log consultation\n- Finally dispatching to configured receivers/integrations\n\n**7. Notification Log:**\nThe `Log` struct (in `vendor/github.com/prometheus/alertmanager/nflog/nflog.go`, line 18) maintains an append-only log of notifications to prevent duplicate notification attempts. It tracks which alerts have been sent to which receivers and supports queries for deduplication across the cluster.\n\n**Complete Flow:**\nWhen an alert fires, it is ingested into `mem.Alerts` and triggers the dispatcher's alert subscription channel. The dispatcher traverses the routing tree to find matching routes, creates aggregation groups, applies the notification pipeline which includes inhibition and silence checks, consults the notification log, and finally dispatches notifications to the matching receivers/integrations. The entire pipeline is coordinated in `ApplyConfig()` which creates the dispatcher, inhibitor, and pipeline builder, then starts them with `dispatcher.Run()` at line 579 and `inhibitor.Run()` at line 580.\n"
}

